AKURE – Governor Oluwarotimi Akeredolu of Ondo State has placed a total ban on commercial motorcycle (okada) operation on the Benin-Ore highway. Acciording to a statement issued by Donald Ojogo, the state’s Commissioner for Information, made available to DAILY INDEPENDENT, the state government took the decision due to the high rate of crimes being perpetrated on the road. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network The ban, according to Ojogo took immediate effect from Ofosu axis of the road which bordered Edo State down to the border town of Ajebamidele, which linked Ogun State, both in Odigbo Local Government area of Ondo State. According to the statement, which mandated the police to arrest any okada rider that violated the ban, “Security agencies, especially the Nigeria Police, are consequently directed to apprehend forthwith, anyone who flouts this restriction order.” Following the ban, okada operation had been restricted to only the inner town of Ore and the adjoining communities. The statement read, “Government has observed with serious concern, the activities of some unscrupulous elements who have hidden under the guise of engaging in motorcycle business, popularly known as Okada, to perpetrate crime on the Ofosu-Ajebamidele route along the Ore Expressway. “Disturbed by the activities of these criminal elements, which include armed robbery, kidnapping, their mode of operations as well as the heightening cases of loss of lives, the Ondo State government has placed a total ban on commercial motorcycles (Okada) along the entire stretch of the route in question. This action is with immediate effect and shall suffice until further notice. “By this development, all activities of commercial motorcyclists are henceforth, restricted to internal confines of Ore town and other communities in the area. security agencies, especially the Nigeria Police, are consequently directed to apprehend forthwith, anyone who flouts this restriction order.